    "4f, multiple red squares per column).",
    "We also found consistencies between these results and prior work on specific LC types-for example, LC16, LC17, and LPLC1 contribute to the angular velocity of the male in our model (Fig. 4f, ' vary female size'), and, if optogenetically activated, also drive turns 12, 26.",
    "The results for these simple stimuli differed slightly from those for natural courtship stimuli (for example, white squares for LC12 in Fig. 4f and red squares for LC12 in Fig.",
    "4c), suggesting that LC contributions change with context.",
    "Overall, our results support the notion that a majority of model LC units are required for the courtship behaviour of the male."
